properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Cold and blustery week A transition to colder conditions has begun across northern and central British Columbia. The cold air will persist through the end of the week with temperatures in the -15C to -25C range. Blustery northerly winds will accompany the arrival of the arctic air with wind chill continuing to be a factor today and tonight. In the wake of the front, the arctic air over the interior will deepen and temperatures will continue to drop Thursday and Friday. People working and spending time outside are reminded to dress warmly and in layers, preferably with a wind-resistant outer layer. Travellers are encouraged to add winter emergency kits to their vehicles which include a blanket, extra clothes and boots. For more cold weather preparedness tips, visit: https://www.canada.ca/en/environment-climate-change/services/seasonal-weather-hazards/be-prepared-for-winter.html#toc5 ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

Description: A significant snowfall is expected today. Snow is expected to continue today and into this evening. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential for Significant Snowfall and Strong Winds Friday night through Sunday morning. Locations: along the coast from L'Anse Au Clair to Hopedale and inland to Upper Lake Melville. Snowfall - Possible Accumulations: 15 to 30 cm Time span: beginning Friday night and ending overnight Saturday night. Remarks: Periods of rain, drizzle and snow is expected to continue along the Labrador coast for the rest of this week. On Friday night, a new low pressure system will approach from the south and cause the precipitation to intensify. Generally snow is expected inland while coastal areas of southeastern Labrador may see some mixing with rain. It is too soon to accurately predict snowfall totals. However, at this time, it is not likely areas along the Strait will see any major accumulations. Wind - Possible wind gusts: 90 to 120 km/h. Time span: Saturday morning to Sunday morning. Remarks: Winds will strengthen out of the northeast on Friday night and potentially reach warning criteria by early Saturday. Strong wind gusts will continue and gradually shift to northwesterly by Saturday night. Coastal areas will have the greatest chance of seeing the strongest wind gusts. Due to uncertainty, specific locations for strongest gusts will be provided in subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Roseau River From Gardenton To Dominion City
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Roseau River from Gardenton to Dominion City due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A prolonged period of snow continues for southwestern Alberta. Total snowfall amounts will be from 25 to 40 cm with some localities possibly exceeding 50 cm. Additionally, gusty northerly winds will produce near zero visibilities in blowing snow. The snowfall is expected to end on Thursday. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A variety of wintry weather and strong winds are expected. Time span: Friday through Saturday. Locations: across Newfoundland as outlined below. For eastern Newfoundland: A snow/rain mix is expected to begin early Friday morning and change to all rain by Friday afternoon. Periods of rain will then persist through Saturday. Significant rainfall amounts are likely and warnings may be required. For central and northeastern Newfoundland: A snow/rain mix will begin Friday morning and persist through Saturday. Significant snowfall amounts are likely inland with rain along the coast and warnings may be required. Winds will also be strong especially along the coast. For western Newfoundland: Periods of snow will begin Friday afternoon and persist through Saturday. Strong northerly winds will accompany the snow Friday night into Saturday, resulting in the potential for reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Warnings may be required. Remarks: It is too early to forecast precipitation amounts for specific areas. Anyone planning travel should prepare for winter driving conditions. Alerts and forecasts issued by Environment and Climate Change Canada will be updated as more information becomes available. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain today. A band of freezing rain may persist into the afternoon before changing over to rain or wet snow. Snowfall amounts will range from 2 centimetres or less near Burks Falls to near 10 cm over higher elevations in Algonquin Park and near the Quebec border. Hazardous winter travelling conditions are expected. Motorists should allow for extra time to reach their destination. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
